Capstone Final Report - London house prices

Jaymin Mistry

22 April 2017

Problem

Property prices in London are already high, this is partly due to large demand and insufficient supply. I want to understand the factors that contribute to differences in house prices for similar type properties within the Greater London area with open source data (access to transport, facilities, schooling etc). I am curious whether there are factors that are not normally considered when searching for a property that affect values and what weighting they have relative to each other.

Audience and output

This information will primarily be useful to anyone considering purchasing a property in London. It would also be useful for estate agents and the property listing websites in the UK (Zoopla, Rightmove and Onthemarket) to identify trends.

For house purchasers, this may highlight areas, which are underpriced and offer good value. Alternatively it may highlight areas, which have similar characteristics but are not regularly considered. For estate agents and property websites, it could provide a guide to understanding what people are actually looking for and therefore provide alternatives. This information would be useful for central and local government in understanding people’s desires and requirements when choosing a home and could therefore focus where resources and effort is spent on development.

What important fields and information does the data set have?

The Land registry dataset contains price paid, date of sale and the property type. It also includes whether it is a freehold or leasehold property and it indicates whether it is a new build property or not. This will only allow me to infer the age of properties built since 1995.

The Metropolitan crime dataset breaks down crime rates into major and minor categories and is split down into anonymised areas at LSOA (Lower Layer Super Output Area) level with a mean size of 1500 people.

There is a huge amount of data available for schooling across the Uk, including money spent the pupil, GCSE results (aged 16), school leaver destinations and A level results (age 18) and destination. I have decided to use GCSE results as a proxy for school quality. GCSE results are a broad indicator of A level performance and therefore overall school performance.

Limitations i.e. what are some questions that you cannot answer with this data set?

The key difficulty I faced is that I am attempting to correlate geospatial data in R. Constructing geospatial models to calculate times is possible but difficult in R and a distraction from the problem I am attempting to solve. Using absolute distance from a central point is possible would mask regions, which are centrally located but poorly served by public transport and vice versa. There is a google maps distance matrix API, which can provide journey times via public transport. However it is limited to 2.5k queries a day.

  1. I have not been able to acquire data on the number of rooms. I assess this is a major factor in house prices but I cannot get access to any dataset containing this information.

  2. I have not found a data set containing ages of property (although this can be deduced for new build properties since 1995)

  3. Crime data is anonymised to month and LSOA.

  4. It is impossible to see whether children go to school across council boundaries or attend boarding school. I am therefore going to assume that the majority of children attend schools within their council area.

A deeper dive into the data set:

The key data set is the prices paid for property from the Land Registry, which lists the majority of property sales since 1995.

Postcodes were randomly sampled from the total sales database, outliers were removed (prices below 100k and above 5 million). The city of London was also excluded, as it comprised a small proportion of residential sales and had a distorted crime and education scores. Here is a summary of the random sample I used (~10.9k properties). Comparing the values subjectively, the sample reflects the overall dataset.

What kind of cleaning and wrangling did you need to do?

The Land Registry Dataset was downloaded complete with all transactions from 1995 to the present day, the file was 3.8Gb. This was split into 10 segments, imported and filtered in R to give ~ 3 million property transactions in London. From this I extracted all sales from 1 Jan 16 till present (13 months), which yielded ~115k sales.

To minimise the number of queries I need, I have simplified it to unique postcodes, for which there are ~60k. I have used the google maps distance API via gmapsdistance package in R to calculate the journey time for each address. I sampled this dataset to collect a random portion, as I was limited to the number of queries I could make.

Gmapsdistance API.

To calculate journey times and therefore assign a value to how accessible each address is, I used the Google maps distance matrix API to calculate the time a public transport journey would take from a postcode to a point in central London (in this case UCL: WC1 6BT). This score I am using a proxy for accessibility to transport. This is imperfect as many people do not work in the city centre, some drive to work and some people commute out of London, it provides the best numerical score without constructing my own spatial models.

There was a limit of 2500 requests per day, so I have randomly sampled 10,000 postcodes from the dataset to calculate times for. As postcodes cover a small geographical area, there is minimal time difference between the different addresses within each.

temp <- gmapsdistance(set.api.key("xxx"),
                         origin = london2[1:500,1],
                         destination = "WC1E6BT",
                         mode = "transit",
                         dep_date = "2017-05-02",
                         dep_time = "09:00:00",
                         combinations = "all")

This produces 3 lists, which are then manipulated with a lapply function to produce a single dataframe.

res <- data.frame(origin = london1[, 1],
                  desination = 'WC1E6BT',
                  do.call(data.frame, lapply(temp, function(x) x[, 2])))

The final output is a time in seconds to make a journey from the start postcode to WC1 6BT, using the best combination of walking and public transport.

Preliminary Exploration

Having examined the prices for London property sold since 1 Jan 16, I explored the type and value of properties sold in this period.

The data above shows that almost half of sales over this period were of flats. It also highlights there is a “O” category. After consulting the Land Registry key, this is residential properties, which do not fall into the other categories and include residences with mixed uses (e.g. a shop combined with a flat). I will remove these from my final analysis.

Approach taken

After collecting results from the Gmaps API, I added these times and distance to the price paid data along with crime and education information. This dataset had 11,040 unique values.

I then tested a variety of linear regression models

Model

Time

qplot(log(Time), log(Price), data = london.complete, colour = District)

Examining the scatterplot of log(time) vs log(Price) demonstrates few no discernable trends. Fitting a regression line for each District results in a positive correlation in some cases but is mainly inconclusve.

### Outputs

Unsurprisingly house prices correlate with an extremely high significance with the factors highlighted I examined (Crime, education and journey time). It is important to note that the crime rate (calculated as the total crime per unit population) is the biggest correlating factor with high property price, closely followed by education (using average GCSE scores as a proxy). This is approximately 27-30 times more important than journey time to central London.

Whilst individual factors correlate significantly with prices, I have not been able to create an effective regression model. This is due to the large variation in the data set. The price data has a standard deviation of ~440k. Removing the major outliers has reduced this but my model still only has an adjusted R squared score of 0.2282. I suspsect that access to further information (size of property, number of rooms and age of property) would allow me to subset the data and produce a better linear model. The Q-Q plots show there is a linear relationship between factors over part of the range of data.

Take away points

Home buyers: Properties in areas with higher crime rates but on the edges of Districts and therefore access to better schools in adjacent Districts may provide the opportunity to acquire an underpriced property

Property Websites: Inclusion of a crime rating and a graphical representation of this are features that are likely to assist buyers with selecting a property.

Government: Reducing crime levels may be the best way of improving the desirability of an area, alongside the quality of the schooling. Public transport is a significant factor but not as critical.

The R code used to wrangle and model the data can be found here: https://github.com/JJmistry/Foundations-of-data-science

Further work

This project could be developed further in two key way: examining the problem in more detail and a wider range of factors to construct a better model. Alternatively more effort could be placed in presenting the information in a accessible way and making it usable to non-technical users, for example interactive mapping.

  1. Examine data with greater granularity (down to LSOA level)
  2. Further factors (green space, air pollution etc)
  3. Examine historical trends
  4. Compare price growth relative to changes (macro â government policy, micro â changes in local policy)
  5. Plot results on an interactive R Shiny map.
  6. Examine only one District but to a greater level of detail.
